******
[1] Newswire
Date: 11 Nov 2012
Source: Examiner [edited]
http://www.examiner.com/article/darfur-yellow-fever-outbreak-deaths-rise-to-85-virus-reaches-khartoum


Yellow fever is caused by a virus carried by mosquitoes, and it is a common disease in South America and in sub-Saharan Africa.

Cases from the yellow fever outbreak in the Darfur region of western Sudan continue to rise, as the World Health Organization (WHO) Sudan reports 266 suspected cases in 20 localities, according to the WHO news release of 9 Nov 2012. Of the 266 cases, 85 fatalities have been reported, which equates to a case fatality rate of 32 per cent.

According to surveillance data, Central Darfur is still the hardest hit area, accounting for 73 per cent of all cases. This is followed by West Darfur (12 per cent), South Darfur (11 per cent), with North and East Darfur accounting for the remainder.

Member of Parliament Ibrahim Abbaker said last week that the outbreak in Darfur has reached "epidemic levels" that require immediate intervention from the central government.

The Ministry of Health in the capital city of Khartoum has even reported the emergence of the 1st case of the mosquitoborne viral disease in the Sudanese capital, according to a Radio Dabanga report on Saturday [10 Nov 2012].

The yellow fever vaccination plan, which will cover 3 587 772 persons in the age group 9 months and above, has been finalized. However, this depends on the reconfirmation of the diagnosis by the reference laboratory, the Institute Pasteur, in Dakar, Senegal, according to a WHO Situation Report on Friday [9 Nov 2012].

To date, more than 100 medical doctors and medical assistants have been trained in South Darfur on disease surveillance, case management, outbreak investigation, and infection prevention and control.

WHO says the 266 suspected cases have presented to health facilities with common symptoms, including fever, bleeding, and vomiting in 99, 64 and 58 per cent of the cases, respectively.

