******
[2] WHO release
Date: 9 Nov 2012
Source: WHO/EMRO press release [edited]
http://www.emro.who.int/sdn/sudan-news/yellow-fever-6november.html


The yellow fever outbreak has now affected 20 localities in Central, South, West, and North Darfur. As of [8 Nov 2012], 266 suspected cases have been reported, including 85 deaths (case fatality rate of 31.8 per cent).

Reports have been received since the last week of September 2012 from the districts of Zalengei, Nertity, Wadisalih, Azoom, Mukjer, Bendisi, Nyala, Kass, Kubum, Sharq Agabal, Yassin, Mershingm, Rehaid Albirdy, Genaina, Kernik, Baidha, Habila, Forbranga, Saraf Omra, and Alseraif.

Surveillance shows that 72.9 per cent of the reported cases are from Central Darfur; 10.9 per cent are from South Darfur; 12 per cent are from West Darfur; 4.1 per cent are from North Darfur, and 0.1 per cent are from East Darfur.

WHO has been assisting the technical support teams deployed by the Federal Ministry of Health in Central, South and West Darfur for initial support and to conduct outbreak investigations, initiate responses, entomological surveys, active case searches, and to hold meetings with community leaders in affected areas to raise awareness, as well as to provision blood bank supplies and personal protective equipment to affected states.

To date, health cadres in affected areas have been vaccinated against yellow fever. Moreover, WHO and the Ministry of Health have started training programmes for more than 225 health staff in the affected localities on yellow fever surveillance, case management, outbreak investigation, and infection prevention and control. On [6 Nov 2012], training programmes for medical doctors on yellow fever surveillance, case definition, and management started in Nyala and Kass localities in South Darfur.

